To push messages to Kafka from a PostgreSQL stored procedure, you can use a connector like the Kafka Connect JDBC sink connector. The connector allows to stream data from the database to Kafka. 

First, you will need to install the connector on your Kafka cluster. Then, in the stored procedure, you can use the `NOTIFY` command to trigger the connector to push data to Kafka. Here is an example:

```
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION push_to_kafka(data text) RETURNS void AS $$
BEGIN
    PERFORM pg_notify('push_to_kafka', data);
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;
```

In this example, the stored procedure takes a `text` parameter which represents the data to be pushed to Kafka. The `pg_notify` command will trigger the Kafka Connect JDBC sink connector to stream this data to Kafka. 

You can then use the `listen` command in your application to listen for notifications and process the data in real time.

The Session class in Laravel is a powerful tool that enables you to store and retrieve data for a user between requests. You can use it to maintain data like user preferences, shopping cart items, and more. 

To use the Session class in Laravel, you simply need to call the `session()` helper function. For example, `session()->put('key', 'value')` will store the value "value" under the key "key" in the user's session. You can then retrieve the value by calling `session()->get('key')`.

There are many other methods available on the Session class, which you can read about in the Laravel documentation.
